Here is a validated bibliography for the cirrus-cloud Fortran model work, focused on the papers that directly support the model choices: parcel modeling, supersaturation variability, nucleation sensitivity, deposition-growth physics, and two-bin/size-distribution motivation.

Core paper used for the simulation concept

1. Kärcher, B., Jensen, E. J., Pokrifka, G. F., & Harrington, J. Y. (2023). Ice Supersaturation Variability in Cirrus Clouds: Role of Vertical Wind Speeds and Deposition Coefficients. Journal of Geophysical Research: Atmospheres, 128(22), e2023JD039324.
DOI: 10.1029/2023JD039324.
Why it belongs: this is the strongest direct match to your demo, because it studies how cirrus supersaturation responds to vertical wind speeds and ice growth assumptions in an air-parcel framework. 



Parcel-model and nucleation sensitivity foundation

2. Lin, R.-F., Starr, D. O’C., Reichardt, J., DeMott, P. J., Cziczo, D., et al. (2002). Cirrus Parcel Model Comparison Project. Phase I: The Critical Components to Simulate Cirrus Initiation Explicitly. Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 59(15), 2305–2329.
Why it belongs: this is the classic reference for why cirrus parcel models are highly sensitive to nucleation and microphysics, which is exactly why we upgraded from a one-shot trigger to a nucleation-rate law. 


3. Lin, R.-F. et al. (2000). Cirrus Parcel Model Comparison Project. NASA Technical Report.
Why it belongs: the NASA report states the project’s primary goal is to identify cirrus-model sensitivities to nucleation and microphysics, making it a solid supporting source for the parcel-model architecture. 



Deposition-growth and supersaturation physics

4. Comstock, J. M., Ackerman, T. P., & Turner, D. D. (2008). Understanding ice supersaturation, particle growth, and number concentration in cirrus clouds. Journal of Geophysical Research: Atmospheres, 113, D23211.
DOI: 10.1029/2008JD010332.
Why it belongs: this paper directly links ice supersaturation, particle growth, and number concentration, and discusses the role of the deposition coefficient in cirrus modeling. That is the key reason for replacing the crude bulk sink with a more explicit growth law. 


5. Westbrook, C. D., & Heymsfield, A. J. (2011). Ice Crystals Growing from Vapor in Supercooled Clouds between −2° and −22°C: Testing Current Parameterization Methods Using Laboratory Data. Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 68(10), 2416–2428.
Why it belongs: this is a strong primary source for capacitance-based vapor growth theory, which supports the step from a tuned bulk deposition term toward a more physical per-crystal growth law. 



Observed supersaturation context

6. Krämer, M. et al. (2009). Ice supersaturations and cirrus cloud crystal numbers. Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 9, 3505–3522.
Why it belongs: this gives observational context for the relationship between ice supersaturation and crystal number, which is central to why nucleation rate and growth law matter so much in the model. 



Why a multi-bin or two-bin extension is justified

7. Zhao, Y., & Garrett, T. J. (2011). The Occurrence of Particle Size Distribution Bimodality in Midlatitude Cirrus as an Indicator of Dynamic Instability. Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 68(6).
Why it belongs: this supports the motivation for moving beyond a single mean radius to a two-bin or broader size-distribution representation, because cirrus particle size distributions can be bimodal. 



Useful recent follow-on context

8. Kärcher, B. et al. (2024). Effects of Turbulence on Upper-Tropospheric Ice Supersaturation. Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences.
Why it belongs: useful as a next-step reference if you later replace sinusoidal forcing with stochastic or turbulence-driven forcing. 



About latent heat in the model

9. Source note for latent-heat feedback: one recent cirrus nucleation study indicates latent heating can be small in some cirrus parcel setups, which is why I treated latent heat as an important but secondary upgrade after nucleation. The exact article surfaced in prior validation as an AGU paper on cirrus nucleation and supersaturation behavior. 



